{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context\nThe identity epic shipped the merge-gate as `.github/workflows/verify-identity.yaml`, which walks\nthe MERGED LOG (CLI `rebar verify-identity`, `src/rebar/_commands/verify_authorship.py`). Its\nenforcement posture and grandfather boundary are read from **rebar.toml**\n(`identity.require_authenticated`, `identity.enforce_since`) — the workflow step is a bare\n`run: rebar verify-identity` with NO CI flags/vars. This story adds a **required-environment op-cert\nverification lane** that mirrors that gate: same merged-log walk, config-driven posture/boundary,\nreusing the shared verify-identity CI job rather than a parallel walker.\n\n**Op-cert storage shape (delivered by keystone e4df).** An op-cert is stored on a ticket as an\n`attestations[<kind>]` record carrying a DSSE `envelope` (`signing.sign_opcert_manifest` writes it;\n`opcert.opcert_from_record` reads it back to `(envelope, {material_fingerprint, merged_log_commit})`).\nThis story READS that shape over the merged log; ee0b's trusted server and 8f1d's migration PRODUCE\nit. A fixture synthesizes one via `sign_opcert_manifest`. **Which kind:** the lane targets the\n**`completion-verifier`** attestation kind — it reads `attestations[\"completion-verifier\"]` (the\nclose-gate op-cert; the `attestations` map is kind-keyed, so the key is fixed by the lane, not\nguessed) and treats a ticket with no `completion-verifier` op-cert as \"absent\" for the enforcement\ncheck below.\n\n**Config-driven posture/boundary (mirror `identity.*`).** Add `verify.opcert_enforce_since`\n(grandfather boundary, mirroring `identity.enforce_since`); `verify.require_environment` (which\nenvironment must sign; already shipped in 42d1) is the posture. The workflow step is a bare\n`run: rebar verify-opcert` — NO CI variable — reading both from rebar.toml, exactly as\n`verify-identity` reads `identity.*`. The lane stays advisory until `verify.opcert_enforce_since`\ncovers op-cert-bearing commits and `verify.require_environment` is set, so adding it does not flip\nthe repo to blocking before producers (ee0b/8f1d) exist.\n\n**Grandfathering the ABSENCE case (the missing-op-cert enforcement anchor).** `verify-identity`'s\n`_is_enforced(commit_sha, since_ref)` tests the commit that introduced *an event*. A ticket that\ncarries NO op-cert has no such event/commit. Resolution: the enforcement anchor for a ticket\nlacking a required-environment op-cert is the commit that introduced the ticket's **terminal\n`STATUS` event** — the status-change event whose target status is `closed` (rebar has no separate\n\"CLOSE\" event type; closure is a `STATUS` event, per `_store/event_append.py`). That event's\nintroducing commit is resolved with the same `authorship.resolve_event_commit` mechanism, then fed\nto `_is_enforced` against `verify.opcert_enforce_since`: a ticket whose close-`STATUS` event\npredates the boundary is grandfathered (advisory pass); one after it is enforced, so a\nmissing/foreign op-cert fails. A ticket with no close-`STATUS` event yet (not closed) is out of\nscope for the completion-verifier lane.\n\n**Per-ticket walk.** `verify_authorship.py`'s merged-log helpers (`_collect_all`/`_collect_range`,\n`_ScopedEvent`) yield per-EVENT; op-cert enforcement is per-TICKET. `verify-opcert` reuses those\nhelpers to enumerate the in-scope event set, then **groups by `ticket_id`** and evaluates each\nticket once, rather than re-implementing the walk.\n\n**Edit targets.** `src/rebar/_commands/verify_opcert.py` (new CLI, mirroring `verify_authorship.py`);\n`src/rebar/_cli/__init__.py` (add a `verify-opcert` equality-test intercept arm alongside the\nexisting `verify-identity`/`verify-commit-ticket` arms); `src/rebar/_config_schema.py` (add\n`verify.opcert_enforce_since`); `.github/workflows/verify-identity.yaml` (add the op-cert step +\nthe CI-trigger audit comment).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A CLI entrypoint `rebar verify-opcert` (in `src/rebar/_commands/`, mirroring\n      `verify_authorship.py`) reads `verify.require_environment` + `verify.opcert_enforce_since` from\n      config (with optional `--require-environment` / `--since` overrides), walks the merged log's\n      tickets (reusing the merged-log walk helper), groups by ticket, and for each in-scope ticket\n      verifies its required-kind op-cert via `rebar.attest.trusted_env.verify_required_environment`\n      (reading the stored op-cert with `opcert.opcert_from_record`). Exit 1 iff an ENFORCED in-scope\n      ticket lacks a valid required-environment op-cert; else exit 0 (advisory). A unit test asserts\n      the exit-code contract.\n- [ ] `.github/workflows/verify-identity.yaml` gains an op-cert verification **step** (same job /\n      same merged-log walk, config-driven posture/boundary — NOT a parallel job) that is a bare\n      `run: rebar verify-opcert` (no CI variable). A test asserts the workflow file contains a\n      `rebar verify-opcert` step.\n- [ ] A fixture test proves the gate: a ticket carrying a valid op-cert (via `sign_opcert_manifest`,\n      env key pinned in a fixture `.rebar/trusted_environments.yaml`, `verify.require_environment`\n      set, and `verify.opcert_enforce_since` before the ticket's close) PASSES; a ticket missing the\n      op-cert, and one whose op-cert is signed by a foreign (non-pinned) key, both FAIL. Fixture in\n      `tests/interfaces/lifecycle/` or `tests/unit/test_verify_opcert.py`; the test names the\n      command it runs.\n- [ ] CI-trigger audit as a concrete artifact: a comment block in\n      `.github/workflows/verify-identity.yaml` enumerates its `on:` triggers and classifies each\n      INCLUDED (op-cert lane runs under it) or NO_FILTER (no `paths`/`branches` filter excludes an\n      op-cert-bearing change); a test asserts the audit comment is present and lists every trigger.\n\n## Remediation: verify-side authoritative-input rule (security finding #4, 2026-07-13)\n\nChange 664's review surfaced a fourth security finding: the gate verifies the cert against\n`material_fingerprint`/`merged_log_commit` read from the SAME attacker-writable stored record the\nenvelope came from (`src/rebar/_commands/verify_opcert.py:163-178`) — a circular check proving\nonly internal consistency. Any tickets-branch writer can store a stale-but-self-consistent cert\n(e.g. one minted before the acceptance criteria were edited) and pass. The fix follows the\nepic's \"Verify-side authoritative-input rule\": the verifier trusts only signed envelope contents\nand state it fetched/computed itself.\n\n- **Recompute the material**: the gate already fetches the authoritative ticket state in its own\n  merged-log walk (`show_ticket` per ticket); it recomputes `material_fingerprint` from that\n  state with the same fingerprint function the producer uses and passes the RECOMPUTED value as\n  the expected subject binding — never the record's claim.\n- **Constrain the commit**: `merged_log_commit` cannot be recomputed, so it is read only from the\n  signature-verified payload (verify-then-extract; the record's plaintext mirror is a display\n  hint), then required to (a) resolve to a real commit that is an ancestor of the fetched `main`\n  tip and (b) satisfy the era/enforcement floors (`verify.opcert_enforce_since`, the pinned\n  key's `added_at_commit` era check, unchanged). Unresolvable/foreign values fail closed.\n- Residual (documented, accepted per ADR 0046 L1 / deferred ticket 2422): a since-revoked\n  trusted key backdating a cert to a commit inside its formerly-valid era, bounded by the\n  recomputed-material requirement + revocation + the enforce-since floor.\n\n### Additional Acceptance Criteria (finding #4)\n- [ ] The gate recomputes `material_fingerprint` from authoritative ticket state: a test stores a\n      SELF-CONSISTENT cert+record whose bound material does not match the ticket's current\n      authoritative material and asserts the gate FAILS it (`mismatch`), while the same cert\n      passes when the ticket state matches.\n- [ ] `merged_log_commit` is taken from the signature-verified payload and constrained: a test\n      asserts a bound commit that is not an ancestor of the fetched history FAILS closed, and\n      that mutating the record's plaintext `material_fingerprint`/`merged_log_commit` fields\n      (envelope untouched) does not change the verdict in either direction."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783999274059029001,"uuid":"5d073488-12ab-4e9a-8981-ae5557f72f52"}